.TH OB-RECORD-CONNECT 1 "June 2026" "open-bastion" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ob-record-connect \- unprivileged connector for the session-recording sink
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ob-record-connect
.I HEADER_JSON
.I CMD
.RI [ ARGS ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ob-record-connect
is the unprivileged half of the tamper-evident session-recording flow. It is
invoked by
.BR ob-session-recorder (8)
(running as the logged-in user); you do not normally run it by hand.
.PP
It connects to the local Unix socket served by
.BR ob-record-sink (8)
(default \fI/run/open-bastion/rec.sock\fR), moves the connected socket to file
descriptor 3 (kept open across
.BR exec ),
writes the one-line JSON metadata
.I HEADER_JSON
to it, then
.BR exec s
.I CMD
\fIARGS\fR \(em typically
.BR script (1)
writing its typescript to \fI/dev/fd/3\fR, which streams the recording straight
into the socket.
.PP
A POSIX shell cannot open an
.B AF_UNIX
socket (a \fBexec 3<>\fR redirection opens regular files/FIFOs only), which is
why this small C helper exists. It carries no privilege and holds no secret: the
sink derives the recorded user from the connection's
.B SO_PEERCRED
(kernel-verified), so the header cannot make the sink write under another
user's name.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B OB_RECORD_SOCKET
Override the socket path (default \fI/run/open-bastion/rec.sock\fR).
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
The command was exec'd (its own exit status then applies).
.TP
.B 1
Could not reach the sink, or an I/O error occurred. The command is
.B not
exec'd \(em recording is mandatory, so the caller fails closed.
.TP
.B 2
Usage error.
.TP
.B 127
The command could not be exec'd.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /run/open-bastion/rec.sock
The session-recording socket
.RB ( ob-record.socket ).
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ob-record-sink (8),
.BR ob-session-recorder (8)
.SH AUTHOR
Linagora
